@node "AboutHelp" "About this help guide       [V3.220 (21.04.96)]"
This is the Commodore Helping System AmigaGuide®. To get more information
about it, click the HELP gadget above or press the H key.

When running the M&M Editor you can call this guide in two ways:

 · by pressing the HELP key.

 · by selecting a menu item while pressing the HELP key. You will get
   specific information about the selected menu item.

You also can call an @{"Index" link "AutoHeddleyIndex" 0}.
@endnode

@node "Installation" "Installation of Menus & More"
You can easily install M&M by executing the M&M project

   @{fg highlight}Install.M&M@{fg text}

It's in the M&M drawer and can be started by double-clicking. After the menu
screen appears, select "Start Installation" button or press the enter-key.

The main installation routine is based upon an @{b}ARexx script@{ub} - so please
launch the ARexx-System (@{i}RexxMast@{ui}) before starting the installation!

If you don't use ARexx, you have the chance to run a "normal" AmigaDos based
script by selecting the pulldown menu 'Install without ARexx'.


@{u}Some notes about the files used by M&M:@{uu}

Please notice that the "MMEditor" program tries to call the following
files:

  · @{i}PROGDIR:M&M.config@{ui}        the configuration file.

  · @{i}PROGDIR:M&M.icon.info@{ui}     the default project-icon used by MMEditor.
                              Change it, if you want...

  · @{i}PROGDIR:M&M.appicon.info@{ui}  the default AppIcon used by the player
                              when going into iconification-mode

  · @{i}PROGDIR:M&M.guide@{ui}         The AmigaGuide file loading via
                              menu online help



Most examples projects are trying to load their menuscreens from

    @{i}PROGDIR:Examples/@{ui}


Please notice that some projects and the (unchanged) "@{b}RunEditor@{ub}" ARexx
command make use of the original Commodore "Ed" from your workbench disk.
This program should be in your C: directory. Use the @{"ARexx command" link "PlayerRexx" 0}
"@{b}SetEditorCom@{ub}" to change the commandline used by "RunEditor"


The following libraries are used:

    asl.library           Version 36+
    AmigaGuide.library    Version 34+
    diskfont.library      Version 33+
    rexxsyslib.library    Version 36+

They should be in the LIBS: directory.
@endnode

@node "AboutMM" "About Menus & More"
@{u}What can I do with Menus & More?@{uu}

   With Menus & More (M&M) you are able to create @{fg fill}graphic orientated
   screen menus@{fg text}. Once you have installed your own menu, you can easily
   call many programs from one central screen. It's just like designing
   your own graphical user interface without doing any programming.
   All you have to know is how to start your programs from CLI.

   Because of the large amount of options, you are able to produce
   even more than just menus - as the name of program indicates!


@{u}How are these menus constructed?@{uu}

  The basic of all menu projects are screens. These screens are
  nothing else than simple IFF pictures, which can be painted
  easily with programs like DeluxePaint® or similar.
  The screen contains the menu as a picture: Every option to be
  selected has to be drawn as a button. Now you have to tell M&M
  the name of the screen, where the buttons are and finally what
  should be happen, if the menu's user clicks on a button.


Based upon a screen, you can make use of the following elements within a
menu project:

  @{fg fill}buttons@{fg text}       the (painted) buttons mentioned above.
                After selection, a command given by the creator
                of the menu will be executed.

  @{fg fill}menus@{fg text}         the original Amiga Intuition pull-down menus.
                A command is executed after selection, too.

  @{fg fill}displays@{fg text}      a status text on the screen. You can display
                the time, date or the free amount of ram.

When creating and editing a menu with MMEditor, every element (screen,
button, pull down menu and display) has its own window. Cnf.
@{"the MMEditor's window" link "Windows" 0}.


Overview:

                        S C R E E N S
                       /      |      \
                   buttons  menus  displays
                      |       |
                   command command


@{u}How can I create such a menu project?@{uu}

  You have to use the @{"MMEditor" link "MMEditor" 0} program for this purpose.
  Created menus will be stored as menu project on disk. This project file
  contains all information necessary to build the menus. For example
  the filenames of the iff pictures used in the project, which commands
  shall be executed and so on.


@{u}How can I run the menu?@{uu}

  The menus are executed with the @{"MMPlayer" link "MMPlayer" 0} program.
  It loads all necessary files and "plays" the menu.


Another overview about the creating and running of a menu project:


                         ------------
      IFF pictures ----> | MMEditor | -----> creates ------
      (=screens)         ------------                    ||
          /\                                             ||
          ||                                             \/
          ||                                      ----------------
          ||                                      | menu-project |
          ||                                      ----------------
          ||                                              |
          ||                                              |
          ||             ------------                     |
          --- loads ---- | MMPlayer | <------ loads -------
                         ------------
                              ||
                            plays
                              ||
                              ||
                              \/
                             user
@endnode

@node "MMEditor" "MMEditor - the Menus & More Editor"
With the help of the MMEditor program, you are able to create good looking
graphical menus.

@{u}Start from Workbench@{uu}

  · by double-clicking the MMEditor icon.

  · by clicking on a menu project icon, holding the shift-key
    and double clicking the MMEditor icon. The given menu project
    will be opened automatically.

  Note: you can edit the @{"MMEditor's tooltypes" link "EdToolTypes" 0} when working
        with the Workbench.


@{u}Start from CLI@{uu}

  · by typing   1> Stack 8192
                1> MMEditor


After the MMEditor has been started, the @{"MMEditor's screen" link "EdScreen" 0} will be opened.
@endnode

@node "Locale" "Locale.library"
Normally, the language used within MMEditor is english. But you can use
other languages. Currently, only german is available.

So, if you want to create a catalog for another language, please contact @{"me" link "Axel" 0}!
As a donation, you will get a free registration...
@endnode

@node "EdToolTypes" "ToolTypes of MMEditor"
You can change the following tooltypes within the icon's "Information"-
requester:


  @{fg fill}WINDOW@{fg text}=doswin

    "doswin" has to be a legal desciption of a AmigaDos window.
    The outputs of the @{"start commands" link "StartComm" 0} will be printed into this
    window.

    Preset: CON:0/0/400/200/M&M/AUTO/CLOSE/WAIT


  @{fg fill}SCRWINHEIGHT@{fg text}=pixel

    You can change the height of @{"screens window" link "ScrWin" 0} with this tooltype.
    "pixel" has to be greater than 80.

    Preset: 100


  @{fg fill}WINHEIGHT@{fg text}=pixel

    This tooltypes indicates the height of all @{"other windows" link "Windows" 0} (buttons,
    menus and displays). "pixel" has to be greater than 160.
    When pixel is set to -1, the windows will fit perfectly below the
    screens window.

    Preset: -1


  @{fg fill}PLANES@{fg text}=n

    To change the number of planes used by the MMEditor screen.
    1 means 2 Colors
    2 means 4 Colors and so on.

    -1 means: use the same number of planes like the workbench does

    Preset: -1


  @{fg fill}TOPAZEIGHT@{fg text}=on/off

    If set to on, MMEditor will use the topaz.8 font.
    If set to off, MMEditor will use the current system font.
    Note that the MMEditor's GUI is designed for the usage
    of topaz.8. So don't use too large fonts...

    Preset: on


  @{fg fill}FILEBUFFER@{fg text}=bytes

    A bigger filenbuffer uses more memory but speeds up the disk
    operation (load/save).

    Preset = 1024


  @{fg fill}ERRORREPORT@{fg text}=ON/OFF

    If an error occurs within a test run, a complete error message
    will appear, if this tooltype is set to ON.

    Preset: ON


  @{fg fill}PICPATTERN@{fg text}=dospat

    The file requester which appears when a new IFF picture
    is opened, uses an AmigaDos pattern to match out all
    non IFF files. When the preset remains unchanged, only
    files with the suffix ".pic" will be displayed in the file
    requester.

    Preset: #?.pic


  @{fg fill}SHELLSTART@{fg text}=comseq

    This command string will be executed after the menu item
    @{"Extras/Shell" link "LaunchShell" 0} has been selected in the MMEditor.

    Preset: NewShell "CON:0/0/400/200/CLOSE/MMShell/SCREENMMEditor


  @{fg fill}SHELLSTACK@{fg text}=bytes

    If your favourite shell needs a bigger stack, tell it MMEditor
    by this toolype.

    Preset: 4096


  @{fg fill}EDSTART@{fg text}=comseq

    This command string will be executed after the menu item
    @{"Extras/Editor" link "LaunchEditor" 0} has been selected in the MMEditor.

    Preset: C:Ed FROM:CON:0/0/400/200/AUTO/CLOSE/Editor/SCREENMMEditor


  @{fg fill}EDSTACK@{fg text}=bytes

     cnf. SHELLSTACK


  @{fg fill}PAINTSTART@{fg text}=comseq

    This command string will be executed after the menu item
    @{"Extras/Painting" link "LaunchPaint" 0} has been selected in the MMEditor.

    Preset: DPaint:DPaint


  @{fg fill}PAINTSTACK@{fg text}=bytes

    cnf. SHELLSTACK
@endnode

@node "EdScreen" "MMEditor's work screen"
Regarding mode, resolution and colors, the screen opened by MMEditor is a
clone of the workbench screen. But it's design is laid out for using the
topaz.8 font. If you want to use your preferred system font, disable topaz.8
by using the @{"TOPAZEIGHT" link "EdToolTypes" 0} tooltype.

You can change the number of planes used by the editor's screen by editing
the @{"PLANES" link "EdToolTypes" 0} tooltype.

The screen is a public screen with the name 'MMEditor', if you started it
twice (why?!), the name is 'MMEditor.2' and so on.

There will be one @{"window" link "Windows" 0} opened on the screen for every element, which can
be used in a menu.
@endnode

@node "Windows" "MMEditor's windows"
@{u}The screen of MMEditor is devided into different windows:@{uu}

  @{"Screens " link "ScrWin" 0} this window contains the menu's screens

  @{"Buttons " link "ButWin" 0} this window contains the menu's buttons
  @{"Menus   " link "MenWin" 0} this window contains the menu's menus
  @{"Displays" link "DisWin" 0} this window contains the menu's displays


@{u}Open and close a window@{uu}

The Screens-window is open at any case. The three other windows will be
opened, if

  · a screen is loaded by choosing "@{b}New@{ub}" or "@{b}Insert@{ub}" in the Screens-window.
  · a project has been @{"opened" link "Open" 0}.

This is, because you can only create a button or install a pulldown menu if
you have already selected the basic IFF picture, the screen.

You can also switch the button-, menu- or displays-window on or off either
by clicking the close gadget in the upper left corner of the window or by
selecting the menu item @{"Window On/Off" link "SwitchWins" 0}.
          

@{u}Window's position, width and height@{uu}

The @{b}width@{ub} of the windows will be the same as the width of @{"editor's screen" link "EdScreen" 0}.
However, their vertical positions are freely adjustable. The settings can be
stored in the @{"configuration file" link "SaveConfig" 0}.

The @{b}height@{ub} of the windows can be changed by using the @{"tooltypes" link "EdToolTypes" 0}.

When using the standard settings of the window's @{b}position@{ub}, you can make out
the current screen at every time.


@{u}Selecting a window via keys@{uu}

By using the function keys, the windows can easily be switched to the front
of the screen:

  · @{b}[F1]@{ub} to bring the 'Screens' window to front.
  · @{b}[F2]@{ub} "    "    "  'Buttons'    "   "    ".
  · @{b}[F3]@{ub} "    "    "  'Menus'      "   "    ".
  · @{b}[F4]@{ub} "    "    "  'Displays'   "   "    ".

The scrolling of a listview can also be done by pressing the cursor up- or
down-key (jump to the start or end by shifting).
@endnode

@node "ScrWin" "Screens-window"
You can manage all affairs concerning the menu's screens within this
window.

A listview of all screens used by the current menu will be displayed, the
actual screen will be highlighted. Like with any listview in MMEditor, you
can choose the actual screen by using the cursor up or down keys.


With "@{b}Add@{ub}"     you can add a new screen to the list.

With "@{b}Insert@{ub}"  you can insert a screen before the actual screen.

With "@{b}Delete@{ub}"  you can delete the actual screen from the list.

With "@{b}Info@{ub}"    you get some information about the actual
               screen appears. As a new option in V3.20, you will also get
               information about the type of color table used by the ILBM
               screen (4Bit for Non-AGA, 32Bit for AGA pictures)

With "@{b}Testrun@{ub}" you can immediately run and test the current screen.

With "@{b}Edit@{ub}"    you have the chance to set further parameters:

  · the @{"font" link "ScrFont" 0} used by the screen.
    After choosing a new font, the IFF picture will be reloaded.
    This is currently the only way of linking the new font to the
    screen.

  · whether the @{b}title@{ub} shall be displayed or not

  · a command @{b}before@{ub} the screen is loaded.
    The AmigaDos command typed in this field will be executed,
    before the IFF picture is displayed.

  · a command @{b}after@{ub} the screen is loaded.
    The AmigaDos command typed in this field will be executed,
    after the IFF picture is displayed (huh?! shocking!)


@{"More hints concerning screens" link "ScreenHints" 0}
@endnode

@node "StartComm" "Startup commands"
M&M gives you the possibility of starting a dos command before a menu screen
is loaded and one after loading. This can be very useful for initialization
purposes.

Example: It is a good idea to assign a directory to a logical device in
order to link all filenames to this device.

        command before loading: @{i}Assign MyMenu: SYS:M&M/Data@{ui}

        Examples for filenames used within the menu project:
          @{i}MyMenu:FirstPicture.pic@{ui}       (a menu screen)
          @{i}MyMenu:Info.txt @{ui}              (a textfile)

So it's easy to change the directory containing the necessary files without
changing the whole menu.

When assigning MyMenu: to "" (via Assign MyMenu: ""), MyMenu: will always
point to the @{i}current@{ui} directory. I did so within the 'Install.M&M' project.

You are also able to run scripts via 'Execute script' as startup command.

Every time you load a project containing startup-commands into the @{i}MMEditor@{ui},
you will be asked, whether these commands shall be executed or not.


@{u}Please notice the output of your startup commands:@{uu}

   If you started the menu from workbench, you can select the
   output stream via the @{"WINDOW tooltype" link "EdToolTypes" 0} within
   MMEditor or MMPlayer:

        WINDOW=CON:x/y/b/h/Name/Options         (cnf. your DOS manual!)


   If you started M&M from CLI, the CLI window will be the output stream.
@endnode

@node "ScrFont" "Font used by a menu screen"
Every screen used within a menu can have it's own font. This font is used

  · in the screen title

  · in the pulldown menu title

  · by the @{"displays" link "DisWin" 0}
@endnode

@node "ScreenHints" "Some Information about the menu's screens"
The screens are nothing else than IFF pictures, which can easily be created
with programs like DPaint® or similar. Every resolution and depth can be
used, AGA modes are supported.

Since Version 3.20, M&M only stores the screen's filename to the project
file. So you can change the screen's name if you want. M&M will load it and
keep the original button positions. The former "Select a new one" function
within the "@{b}Info@{ub}" Requester has been discarded!

If there is any @{b}error@{ub} while loading the menu's screen, you have the
possibilty to select a new filename.

Also new since Version 3.20 is a (hopefully) correct @{b}AGA color support@{ub}. M&M
now detects a 32 Bit color flag within the IFF ILBM file. If this flag is
set and the graphics library version is >= 39, M&M will use the new AGA
color functions. You can check this flag via the Screen "Info" Requester.

Concerning correct IFF ILBM saving (32 Bit color flag), I made best
experiences with Cloato's® PersonalPaint!

Another problem is the use of masking data. Please switch every mask off
before you save your menu picture to disk!
@endnode

@node "ButWin" "Buttons-window"
This window will only open, if a menu screen has been loaded.

The name of the actual button is displayed below a listview gadget which
contains a list with the names of all used buttons.

"@{b}Add@{ub}"         a new button at the end of the list. After selection,
              you have to @{"set the button's area" link "GetButton" 0}.

"@{b}Insert@{ub}"      a new button before the actual button in the list.
              You have to set the button's area, too.

"@{b}Clear@{ub}"       deletes the actual button from the list.

"@{b}Edit@{ub}"        let's you reset the button's area.


You have to tell MMEditor, which @{"command" link "Commands" 0} should be done after selecting the
current button and whether there should be a @{"parameter request" link "Requests" 0} before
executing or not.

"@{b}Select@{ub}"      the argument passed to the action.
              This can be a file like an AmigaDos command or
              an ARexx programm or the name of a screen, a
              AmigaDos return value...

"@{b}Option@{ub}"      you can set more options concerning the selected command.
              Some commands like 'Quit Menu' don't have any options, so
              the gadget will be ghosted.

"@{b}Key@{ub}"         the button can be selected either by clicking or by
              pressing a corresponding key. Type the key, which
              represents the current button, into this field. If
              you want to use a special key, select the 'Key' gadget.

@{"Click here to get more hints about buttons!" link "ButtonHints" 0}
@endnode

@node "GetButton" "Setting the button's area"
Setting the button's area is done in following way:

  1. The menu screen will be brought to front.
  2. Select the upper left corner of the button with
     the left mouse button.
  3. Hold left mouse button
     (if you want to select another corner, just press the esc key)
  4. go to the button's lower right corner.
  5. release mouse button.

It's not always an easy job to mark just the right area of the button. To
make thi simplier, a function called "@{b}Lasso@{ub}" has been implemented. You
switch Switch it on (and off) with the space bar. Once switched on, you only
have to mark the approximate area, the button will be searched
automatically. Just try it! Please note: The lasso function will only work
if the button has been painted on a @{b}monocoloured@{ub} background!

With the @{b}F10@{ub} key, you can the switch the screen's title while setting the
area of the button.

After the setting procedure, the button's @{b}name@{ub} will be requested. You cannot
use a name twice within a list.
@endnode

@node "ButtonHints" "Some clues concerning the menu's buttons"
There is a problem when you insert a new button in the list: The IDs of the
gadget are not re-calculated every time a new button is inserted. So it is
possible that a button will not be recognized while test-running.

The problem can be solved in two ways:

  1. If you have only one screen: Save the project, select 'New Project'
     and open it again. A test-run will do fine now.

  2. If you have more than one screen, it is easier: just select another
     screen, then select the "fault one". Test-run will be working again.
@endnode

@node "MenWin" "Menus-window"
This window contains a list of all intuition pulldown menu items used within
your M&M menu.

To create such a pulldown menu, select @{"Edit" link "GetMenus" 0}.

Single items can be "@{b}Insert@{ub}"ed or "@{b}Clear@{ub}"ed.

After editing the pulldown menu, you should set

  · the @{"request" link "Requests" 0} and
  · the @{"command" link "Commands" 0}

linked to the different items - just like the way you did it in the
@{"buttons window" link "ButWin" 0}.


@{"Click here to get some hints about menus!" link "MenuHints" 0}
@endnode

@node "GetMenus" "Editing the pulldown menus"
The actual menu screen (your iff picture) will be zapped into the front.

Then a window is opened: Here you can edit your personal menu. All you have
to do is to type the title and the linked items. With "@{b}Add@{ub}" you can add a
new title to your menu or "@{b}Insert@{ub}" a new one.

You can set a menu selection key (right Amiga + X, for example) for every
item.

Jump with the enter key from one item to another, for jumping to the
selection key field use the TAB key (shifted to jump back).

With the cursor left and right key, you can jump from one title to the
next.

By selecting the "@{b}Font@{ub}" gadget, a new font concerning the menu items (only!)
can be choosen. The font of the menus titles is choosen in the
@{"screen edit window" link "ScrWin" 0}.

You are also able to "@{b}Clear@{ub}" one, all or none item(s).

As a new feature since V3.21, the real intuition @{b}barlabels@{ub} are supported
now. M&M will recoqnise them, if the first three characters are '-'.

So '---' will result in a barlabel (also '------' and '---axel').


@{u}Please notice:@{uu}

  The maximum number of titles to be edited is currently 15.

  The maximum number of items is currently set to 15, too.
  BUT: if you use a menu screen with a very small height, the
  space for the editing window is limited - thus the number
  of editable items will be decreasing!
@endnode

@node "MenuHints" "Some Hints concerning pulldown menus"
The highest number of editable menu title is 15. Every title can have 15
items at maximum.

Use the '---' to create Intuition BarLabels...
@endnode

@node "DisWin" "Displays-window"
The Displays-Window contains the following gadgets:

"@{b}Add@{ub}"         adds a new status display to the list.

"@{b}Insert@{ub}"      inserts a new display into the list.

"@{b}Clear@{ub}"       clears an existing display.


@{u}Set up a new status display in the following way:@{uu}

  Selecting "@{b}Edit@{ub}", a window will appear on the menu screen.
  Now you can change

  · the x- and y-position of the text,

  · one string appearing before the specific information to
    be displayed and one string after and

  · the display modus (free memory, time or date), which sets
    the specific information mentioned above.


Set the x- and y-position easily with the mouse by clicking @{b}New position@{ub}.


M&M will construct the status display in the following way:

  [@{i}string before@{ui}] [ ] [@{i}display@{ui}] [ ] [@{i}string after@{ui}]

  Example:      before: "Time:"           \
                 after: "o'clock"          > "Time: 16.24.13 o'clock"
                  mode: "Time - 16.24.13" /

Please notice the space character between the different elements.

And notice too that you cannot change the display's color (it is the
complement of the color underlying the display - try it!).

The last hint worth noticing is the fact that the font of the display is the
@{"menu-screen's font" link "ScrFont" 0} (which you can set in the screen's edit window).
@endnode

@node "AllMenus" "Menus of MMEditor"
The menu of MMEditor is devided into four parts:

@{fg fill}1.Project@{fg text}         @{"New                   " link "New" 0}
                  @{"Open...               " link "Open" 0}
                  @{"Save                  " link "Save" 0}
                  @{"Save as...            " link "Save" 0}
                  @{"Install...            " link "InstallProject" 0}
                  @{"About...              " link "About" 0}
                  @{"Help                  " link "AboutHelp" 0}
                  @{"Quit...               " link "Quit" 0}

@{fg fill}2.Testrun@{fg text}         @{"from current screen   " link "RunCurrScr" 0}
                  @{"from first screen     " link "RunFirstScr" 0}
                  @{"Execute Commands...   " link "PlayerModes" 0}

@{fg fill}3.Settings@{fg text}        @{"Buttons window?         " link "SwitchWins" 0}
                  @{"Menus window?           " link "SwitchWins" 0}
                  @{"Displays window?        " link "SwitchWins" 0}
                  @{"Create Icons?           " link "CreateIcons" 0}
                  @{"Save Settings           " link "SaveConfig" 0}

@{fg fill}4.Extras@{fg text}          @{"Copy commands...     " link "CopyCommands" 0}
                  @{"Launch Shell         " link "LaunchShell" 0}
                  @{"Launch Editor        " link "LaunchEditor" 0}
                  @{"Launch Painting Tool " link "LaunchPaint" 0}
@endnode

@node "New" "Project New"
Select this item to clear the current menu project from memory.

If the project has not been saved before, a requester giving you the chance
to do that, appears.
@endnode

@node "Open" "Open project"
To open an existing menu project from disk. Choose it in the file
requester.

The following @{b}errors@{ub} are possible:

   · the selected file is not an M&M file.
   · the selected file has an incorrect format.
   · there is not enough free memory
   · the IFF file cannot be found or loaded - here you
     get the chance to select another filename
@endnode

@node "Save" "Save project (as)"
To save a menu project to disk.

If you are saving a project the first time - the file name is 'NoName.M&M' -
a file requester will appear.

If your project already has a filename, you can

   "@{b}Save@{ub}"        with the same name

   "@{b}Save as@{ub}"     a new project with a new filename.
@endnode

@node "About" "About..."
You will get information about:

  · the version of MMEditor you are currently using
  · the author @{"Axel Sodtalbers" link "Axel" 0}
  · the copyright
  · the free amount of memory

Further, you can get information about

        @{b}User@{ub}: the registration entry
    @{b}Internal:@{ub} · name of the MMEditor's (!) public screen
              · number of bit-planes used by MMEditor's screen
              · language used by MMEditor (built-in or deutsch)
              · whether MMEditor has found the configuration-file or not
              · whether MMEditor uses topaz.8 or the current system font

              · name of the MMPlayer's (!) public screen
              · name of the Player's ARexx-Port (used within test run)
@endnode

@node "InstallProject" "Install Menu Project"
This function gives you the possibility to install your created menu
automatically in a very easy way. Just select, in which drawer your new menu
shall be copied and all necessary files including screen iff-files and
textfiles with it. The filenames will be changing automatically.

It is also possible to include your menu into the user-startup file in the
S: drawer. The menu will then be executed automatically after every
(re-)start of your Amiga.

You can change the following options:

@{b}Target directory @{ub}             Select the target-directory by clicking
                              this gadget. If you want to create a
                              new drawer for your menu, just type in
                              the desired directory name.

@{b}Create Icon?@{ub}                  For project, screen and textfiles

@{b}Copy Screen IFF-Files?@{ub}        Copy all screens used by the current menu?
                              Filenames will be adopted automatically.

@{b}Copy Text-Files?@{ub}              Copy all textfiles used by the current menu?
                              Filenames will be adopted automatically.

@{b}Insert in S:User-Startup?@{ub}     For Auto-Start your favourite M&M menu
                              after your computer has been turned on or
                              reseted...
@endnode

@node "Quit" "Quit..."
To quit MMEditor.

Do you really want to quit this fabulous program? (sniff!)  :-(
@endnode

@node "RunCurrScr" "Testrun from current screen"
If you want to test the menu, select this item. The test will be started at
the actual menu screen.

Don't forget to implement a @{b}Quit@{ub} button or pulldown menu in your menu by
using the @{i}Quit menu@{ui} command! But you can stop the testrun by pressing the
ctrl- and the esc-key at any time.
@endnode

@node "RunFirstScr" "Testrun from first screen"
This item has the same function as @{"testrun from current screen" link "RunCurrScr" 0} except that
the testrun will always start at the first screen in the list.

Thus the selection will do the same than running the @{"MMPlayer" link "MMPlayer" 0} and is a good
opportunity to test your complete menu.
@endnode

@node "PlayerModes" "Execute commands always/by request/never"
Here you can choose what shall happen if you select a button or menu with a
@{i}Execute dos command@{ui} or @{i}Switch to other screen@{ui} command function while
testrunning.

  @{b}always@{ub}              the dos command will be executed in any case.

  @{b}by request@{ub}          a request appears so that you can select
                      whether the command shall be runned or not.
                      This is recommended if your menu contains
                      "dangerous" functions like deleting files or
                      formating disks...

  @{b}never@{ub}               the dos command won't be executed.

The actual setting will be stored in the @{"configuration file" link "SaveConfig" 0}.

The @{"startup commands" link "StartComm" 0} (before and after loading the menu screen) are
concerned, too.
@endnode

@node "SwitchWins" "Switching a window on or off"
You can close or open any window - execept the screen window by clicking the
close gadget in the upper left corner or by selecting just this menu item.

The three windows (button, menu and display) will only open if there is a
menu screen in memory (cnf. @{"the window system" link "Windows" 0}). Thus these menu items are
only selectable when you have loaded a screen.

The status of any window (opened or closed) can be stored in the
configuration file by selecting @{"save settings" link "SaveConfig" 0}.
@endnode

@node "CreateIcons" "Create Icons?"
If you want a project icon stored to disk together with you menu, select
this item.

If existing, the icon called "@{i}PROGDIR:M&M.icon@{ui}" will be used - otherwise the
standard workbench icon.
@endnode

@node "SaveConfig" "Save settings"
After selecting this item, the current configuration of MMEditor will be
stored in the 'M&M.config' file in the directory, MMEditor has been started
from. It currently contains:

  · the @{"window's" link "Windows" 0} vertical position, opened or not

  · the @{"mode of executing commands" link "PlayerModes" 0} within a testrun

  · the position and size of the file-requester

  · the position and size of the font-requester

  · whether MMEditor shall @{"produce an icon when saving a project" link "CreateIcons" 0} or not
@endnode

@node "CopyCommands" "Copy commands..."
It is very annoying to produce the same actions for many different screens
within one menu project. Too, it is no fun to create one pulldown menu with
the same function for every button.

Thus the possibility to copy commands between buttons, between menus or
between button and menus has been implemented.

After calling this function, a window containing two lists appears: the left
lists marks which function shall be copied, the right one where to.

You can switch every list to a buttons or a menus list.

Use the cursor key alternatively to move whithin the lists: up and down in
the left list, left and right in the right one.

The copy will be done, if the "@{b}Copy@{ub}" gadget has been selected.

If "@{b}incl. Request@{ub}" has been checked, the request will copied, too.

Leave the window via "@{b}Leave@{ub}" (or press esc).
@endnode

@node "LaunchShell" "Launch shell"
You can start a shell on the MMEditor's screen.

The exact command executed after this menu item has been selected can be
changed via the @{"tooltype SHELLSTART" link "EdToolTypes" 0}.

Preset is:

   NewShell "CON:0/0/400/200/CLOSE/MMShell/SCREENMMEditor
@endnode

@node "LaunchEditor" "Launch editor"
You can start an ASCII editor from MMEditor.

The exact command executed after this menu item has been selected can be
changed via the @{"tooltype EDSTART" link "EdToolTypes" 0}.

Preset is:

   C:Ed FROM:CON:0/0/400/200/AUTO/CLOSE/Editor/SCREENMMEditor

IF C:Ed is the original Commodore Ed, it will be started on the screen of
MMEditor.
@endnode

@node "LaunchPaint" "Launch a paint programm"
Finally, you can start a paint program - but remember that a great amount of
free (chip!) memory will be very useful for this purpose!

Preset is:

    DPaint:DPaint

Change the command string by editing the @{"PAINTSTART tooltype" link "EdToolTypes" 0}.
@endnode

@node "Requests" "Requests"
Before a command is executed, M&M can ask the user to give a parameter. This
is done via @{b}requesters@{ub}. The result will be stored in an AmigaDos environment
variable, thus it is easy to use the user's parameter within (mainly
AmigaDos-) commands.

You can either use the AmigaDos command 'GetEnv' (within scripts) or the '$'
character placed before the name of the environment variable. Please confer
the chapter about environment variables (GetEnv/SetEnv) in your AmigaDos
manual to get used to this stuff!

An M&M request uses the following elements:

   · the requester type (1)

   · the requester @{"text" link "ReqText" 0} (2)

   · the name of the @{"environment variable" link "ReqEnvs" 0} (3)
     to which the request's result shall be stored


The following requester types can be used:

   @{i}filename@{ui}
   @{i}directory@{ui}
   @{i}textline@{ui}

   @{i}yes or no@{ui}          (command will only be executed only
   @{i}okay or cancel@{ui}     when user selects yes/okay)

   @{i}information@{ui}        (displaying the requester text only)


                                @{fg highlight}Overview@{fg text}

-----------------------------------------------------------------------
Req.Type   | It appears       | Requester Text is | EnvVar            |
           | (1)              | is (2)            | contains (3)      |
======================================================================|
FILENAME   |file requester    | requester's       | complete filename |
           |                  | title             |                   |
-----------|------------------+-------------------+-------------------|
DIRECTORY  |file requester    | requester's       | directory name    |
           |(directories only)| title             | plus "/"          |
-----------|------------------+-------------------+-------------------|
TEXTLINE   |requester with    | above the textline| text typed by the |
           |textline          |                   | user              |
-----------|------------------+-------------------+-------------------|
YES/NO     |standard system   | requester's text  | nothing.          |
           |requester         |                   | comm. only if yes |
-----------|------------------+-------------------+-------------------|
OKAY/CANCEL|standard system   | requester's text  | nothing.          |
           |requester         |                   | comm. only if okay|
-----------|------------------+-------------------+-------------------|
INFORMATION|standard system   | requester's text  | nothing           |
           |requester         |                   |                   |
-----------------------------------------------------------------------


@{u}Notice:@{uu} Whether your menu requests a FILENAME or a DIRECTORY,
        the selected filename  will ALWAYS be stored to the env.var
        '@{b}MMFile@{ub}' and the selected directory will ALWAYS be stored to the
        env.var '@{b}MMPath@{ub}' for an easy use within scripts. Use it within
        scripts!
@endnode

@node "ReqText" "Requester's text"
The requester's text will appear as the title of the file requester, above
the textline to be edited or just within the standard system requester
(Yes/No, Okay/Cancel and Information).

The text within standard requesters can be wrapped by using the character
'|'

    Example: Hello folks,|how are you?

             will appear as

             Hello folks,
             how are you?

Please confer the example menus.


Since V3.21 you can easily edit the requester's text by selecting the "@{b}text@{ub}"
gadget. A window with 6 textlines each containing 40 characters appears. By
selecting "@{b}Lnk@{ub}", "@{b}Cnt@{ub}" or "@{b}Blk@{ub}" you can justify the textlines: left,
centered or block. You can influence the way of justification by select the
menus (!) "Absolute" or "Relative".

In the next version, the textfield to be edited will be larger than the
current 6x40 matrix...
@endnode

@node "ReqEnvs" "Environment variables"
AmigaDos handles so called environment variables. The contents of those
variables are stored to the logical ENV: device. It's easy to get the
information stored within them.

First, you can use the AmigaDos commands

   @{b}GetEnv@{ub}  to read the env.var.
   @{b}SetEnv@{ub}  to write into the env.var.

Second, you can access the information stored within the env.var by using
the string

   @{b}"$nameofenvironmentvariable"@{ub}

The text 'nameofenvironmentvariable' will automatically replaced by the
content of the env.var!

Example:

        @{b}Request@{ub}: FILENAME       save to: @{i}myFile@{ui}

                 Please select filename!

        @{b}Command@{ub}: EXECUTE DOS COMMAND

                 type "@{i}$myFile@{ui}" to prt:
@endnode

@node "Commands" "Commands"
M&M knows the following commands:

   @{"Dos Commands  " link "CommDos" 0}  execute an AmigaDos command

   @{"ARexx Commands" link "CommRxx" 0}  send an ARexx command

   @{"Text Display  " link "CommTxt" 0}  display a textfile

   @{"Screen Switch " link "CommScr" 0}  switch to another screen

   @{"Brush Display " link "CommBrs" 0}  show iff brush

   @{"Quit Menu     " link "CommStp" 0}  quit the menu

   or do nothing.


Further options are

  @{b}Return@{ub}   Shall M&M return to the menu's execution after the
           command has been executed?

@{b} Options@{ub}   To set more options concerning the selected command

  @{b}Select@{ub}   To select the command's argument, for example the
           AmigaDos/ARexx command itself or the name of the
           the screen M&M should jump to.
@endnode

@node "CommDos" "Execute a AmigaDOS command"
Use this command to run any Amiga program. As you see, this command is the
real @{fg fill}KERNEL@{fg text} of M&M!

After clicking Options, you can influence the following

  @{b}X, Y,@{ub}
  @{b}Width, Height@{ub}  @{"position" link "GetWin" 0} of the output window

  @{b}Title@{ub}          of the output window

  @{b}on Plr Screen@{ub}  output window will appear on the MMPlayer's screen,
                 if not checked: on workbench.

  @{b}Auto Open@{ub}      output window will only appear, if there is really
                 some text to put out.

  @{b}Wait@{ub}           output window will be opened until the user clicks
                 the close gadget or presses ctrl+\.

  @{b}Smart@{ub}          open a smart output window?

  @{b}ASyncron@{ub}       the AmigaDos will be executed a-synron to the other
                 programs, so the user is able to select the next menu
                 item, while this AmigaDos command is still running.

  @{b}Pri.@{ub}           the program's priority within the Amiga Multitasking
                 system.

  @{b}Stack@{ub}          Some programs need more than the obligatory 4000
                 bytes of stack space. Check the program's icon
                 via workbench command 'Icons/Information' to find
                 out the needed amount of memory (or confer the
                 manual of your program).

  @{b}CD@{ub}             The current directory of the program to start.
                 @{i}Hint:@{ui} If you type "@{b}$MMPath@{ub}" into this field, MMPlayer
                 will set the result of a directory request started before
                 as the current directory!

  @{b}SetWaitPointer@{ub} the mouse pointer OF THE MMPLAYER'S WINDOW (!!)
                 will be change when the concerning button has been
                 selected.
                 This option is disabled, when 'ASyncron' is set.

  @{b}Close-Gadget@{ub},
  @{b}not draggable@{ub},
  @{b}no Size-Gadget@{ub},
  @{b}no Border@{ub},
  @{b}Background@{ub}     concerning the look of the output window.
@endnode

@node "CommRxx" "Send an ARexx command"
To send any ARexx command or to execute ARexx scripts. Options are:

@{b}Port@{ub}           sets the ARexx port to which your ARexx command or script
               shall be sent. Please notice that the port displayed within
               the list need not to be ARexx ports!

@{b}Command line@{ub}   select this, if you want to execute just one ARexx command
               line

If you want to execute an ARexx script, you have to select "REXX" as the
port (stands for the 'RexxMast' programm, which should be active while
running the menu).

When selecting "Select" a list of the MMPlayers's internal ARexx commands
appears. If you choose one of them, the @{b}Port@{ub} will be set to "MMPlayer"
automatically.

Remember that the MMPlayer has an @{"ARexx port" link "PlayerRexx" 0} called 'MMPlayer', which will
be active while testrunning from MMEditor, too.
@endnode

@node "CommTxt" "Show a textfile (command)"
Displays an ASCII textfile.

After clicking @{b}Options@{ub}, you can influence the following options

  @{b}X, Y,@{ub}
  @{b}Width, Height@{ub}         the textwindow's @{"position" link "GetWin" 0}.

  @{b}Font@{ub}                  used in the textview window

  @{b}Diplay on Workbench?@{ub}  whether the textwindow shall appear on the menu's
                        screen or on the workbench


You can also easily select the textfile from the editing window.

The text display depends upon the program @{"MMTextview" link "TextView" 0} which is currently not
implemented as a stand-alone program (but will be in future). Looking at the
key functions, it is similar to the original Commodore 'More' program. And
it is a very old program which will be re-programmed in the future.
@endnode

@node "TextView" "Textviewing with M&M"
After loading the ASCII file, there are the following options of cursing
through the text:

  SPACE (or LMB)        next page
  ENTER                 next line
  <                     first page
  >                     last page
  BACKSPACE             previous page
  q or CTRL+C           Quit textview
  h                     Help (back to textview by SPACE)
  F1                    show until 10% of text
  F2                    show until 20% of text
  (...)
  F0                    show until end of text

Jump to the next page by pressing the left mouse button.
@endnode

@node "CommBrs" "Show brush (command)"
The "Show brush" command gives you the ability to display an IFF ILBM brush
file on Player's screen. Options are:

@{b}X, Y,@{ub}                Position of the brush

@{b}File@{ub}                 Filename of the brush

@{b}Display Mode@{ub}         Currently, there are 3 types of displaying the brush:

                     1. Paste, wait and cut
                        Brush will disappear after the user has clicked
                     2. Paste into screen
                     3. Use own window.
                        The user has to close it to go on with the menu.

@{b}Use Brush Palette?@{ub}   Switch to the brush's palette or not. This is
                     not selectable when using brush mode 2


If you call the options window, MMEditor first tries to load the given
brush. So you maybe have to wait a short time. If there is no filename,
there is also no brush and you cannot "@{b}Set@{ub}" the brush's position.

To test the different brush modes, use the "@{i}BigFuncTest.M&M@{ui}" project and
switch to the second menu screen!
@endnode

@node "CommScr" "Switch to other screen (command)"
There are no options you can change. But you can choose the screen you want
to switch to by clicking "@{b}Select.@{ub}" The list of all screens used within the
current menu will appear.

If you just want to show another screen which is not used as a menu screen,
select @{b}other screens@{ub}. This will bring a file-requester on the screen, where
you can choose a IFF file. The display of such a picture can be stopped by
pressing the left mouse button or the space bar. The screen will be closed
and the menu's screen will be brought to front again.

Please notice that the menu's screen will @{i}not@{ui} be closed while showing a
picture, thus you will need enough space for holding many screens (picture,
menu's screen, maybe workbench...) at one time in memory.
@endnode

@node "CommStp" "Quit the menu (command)"
Quits the menu. Uh? Really? - Yes!

The only @{b}option@{ub} available is to "@{b}Clear all environment variables@{ub}" after
quitting the menu. If you did so, you have no access to the variables used
in your menu after it has been terminated.

You can "@{b}Select@{ub}" a AmigaDos return value. There are presets like OKAY, WARN,
ERROR and FAIL (cnf. your favourite AmigaDos manual).

Selecting this command, you cannot change the "@{b}Return@{ub}" field.
@endnode

@node "GetWin" "Set the output window"
The values within the @{b}X, Y, Width and Height@{ub} gadgets are giving the window's
position and measure.

Click @{b}Show@{ub} to bring the window on screen. Now you can change position and
measure directly. The window is closed after @{b}Close@{ub} has been clicked.
@endnode

@node "MMPlayer" "MMPlayer - the Menus & More Player"
@{b}MMPlayer@{ub} is a stand-alone program able to play menus created with the Menus
& More Editor MMEditor.

For this purpose MMPlayer opens a

  · @{"public screen" link "PlayerScr" 0} and an

  · @{"ARexx port" link "PlayerRexx" 0},

both named 'MMPlayer' (or MMPlayer_1 if started twice, and so on).


@{u}Start from Workbench@{uu}

  · by double-clicking the MMPlayer icon. A file-requester appears.
    Now you can select a menu project to load.

  · by clicking on a menu project icon, holding the shift-key
    and double clicking the MMPlayer icon. The given menu project
    will be opened automatically.

  · by typing 'MMPlayer' as the default tool within the workbench
    Icon/Information window.

  Note: you can edit the @{"MMPlayer's tooltypes" link "PlayerToolTypes" 0} when
        working with the Workbench.


@{u}Start from CLI@{uu}

  · by typing   1> MMPlayer [projectname]


The running of a menu can be interrupted by pressing Ctrl+Esc (this
behaviour can be switched off by the @{"tooltype BREAK" link "PlayerToolTypes" 0}).

If there is still an open window on the menu's screen or another task uses
the screen and MMPlayer tries to close the screen, a message will appear.
Then the user of the menu has to close the window or stop the task.
@endnode

@node "PlayerToolTypes" "ToolTypes of MMPlayer"
You can change the following tooltypes within the icon's "Information"-
requester:

  @{fg fill}WINDOW@{fg text}=doswin

    "doswin" has to be a legal desciption of an AmigaDos window.
    The outputs of the @{"start commands" link "StartComm" 0} will be printed into this
    window.

    Preset: CON:0/0/400/200/M&M/AUTO/CLOSE/WAIT


  @{fg fill}ERRORREPORT@{fg text}=ON/OFF

    If an error occurs while runnung a menu, a complete error message
    will appear - if this tooltype is set to ON.

    Preset: ON


  @{fg fill}BREAK@{fg text}=ON/OFF

    Normally you can interrupt the execution of a menu by
    pressing Ctrl+Esc. If you don't want the user to do so,
    switch this behaviour off with BREAK=OFF.

    Preset: ON
@endnode

@node "PlayerRexx" "MMPlayer's ARexx port"
MMPlayer will open an ARexx port automatically after start. It has the name
@{b}MMPlayer@{ub} (@{b}MMPlayer_1@{ub} for a second started MMPlayer and so on).

It is recommended to look at the example ARexx scripts

  - @{i}Install.rexx@{ui}               and
  - @{i}examples/RexxTest.rexx@{ui}

You will find useful hints there about the usage of the following commands!

Currently, the player's ARexx-Port is knowing the following commands:

(Note:  Int = number value
        Str = string value
       Bool = boolean value; 0=FALSE, 1=TRUE)


* COMMAND: @{fg fill}Quit@{fg text}
  PURPOSE: terminates the menu's execution.
     ARGS: -

* COMMAND: @{fg fill}SwitchScreen@{fg text} [@{b}towhich@{ub}:Str]
  PURPOSE: Switch to another screen (same function as the
           button's command @{"Switch to other screen" link "CommScr" 0}
     ARGS: towhich - name of the screen to switch to.
___________________________________________________________________

* COMMAND: @{fg fill}Iconify@{fg text}
  PURPOSE: MMPlayer will be @{"iconified" link "PlayerIco" 0}: the menuscreen will close
           and the MMPlayer's AppIcon ("PROGDIR:M&M.appicon")
           will appear on the workbench.
     ARGS: -

* COMMAND: @{fg fill}Uniconify@{fg text}
  PURPOSE: To re-open the player's menuscreen after iconification
           with "Iconify".
     ARGS: -
     NOTE: Uniconify is synonymous to Wake

* COMMAND: @{fg fill}Sleep@{fg text}
  PURPOSE: The MMPlayer's screen will be closed.
           To open the menu screen, use "wake" or "uniconify"
     ARGS: -

* COMMAND: @{fg fill}Wake@{fg text}
  PURPOSE: After MMPlayer has "gone sleeping" (cf. "Sleep")
           you can re-open the menuscreen using this
           command.
     ARGS: -
     NOTE: Wake is synonymous to Uniconify
___________________________________________________________________

* COMMAND: @{fg fill}AlohaPlayer@{fg text}
  PURPOSE: Brings the Players's screen to front and activates it.
     ARGS: -

* COMMAND: @{fg fill}PlayerPos@{fg text} [@{b}deltaX@{ub}:Int] [@{b}deltaY@{ub}:Int]
  PURPOSE: Moving the Player's screen
     ARGS: deltaX - relative horicontal movement
           delatY - relative vertical movement

* COMMAND: @{fg fill}PlayerToFront@{fg text}
  PURPOSE: Brings the Players's screen to front 
     ARGS: -

* COMMAND: @{fg fill}PlayerToBack@{fg text}
  PURPOSE: Brings the Players's screen to the background.
     ARGS: -
___________________________________________________________________

* COMMAND: @{fg fill}SetTitle@{fg text} [@{b}newtitle@{ub}:Str]
  PURPOSE: Display a new screen title
     ARGS: newtitle - your new screen title

* COMMAND: @{fg fill}SwitchButton@{fg text} [@{b}nr@{ub}:Int] [@{b}on@{ub}:Bool]
  PURPOSE: Switch any button on or off.
     ARGS: nr - number of button.
                0 is the first one in the list, 1 the second,...
           on - 0=discard it. Button will be ghosted
                1=turn it on.
     NOTE: After a button has been turned off, it's display cannot
           be recreated - sorry, I am working on this problem.

* COMMAND: @{fg fill}SwitchTitle@{fg text} [@{b}on@{ub}:Bool]
  PURPOSE: Turning the display of the screen's title on or off
     ARGS: on - 0=don't show the title
                1=show it
___________________________________________________________________

* COMMAND: @{fg fill}Req@{fg text} [@{b}text@{ub}:Str] [@{b}gadget@{ub}:Str]
  PURPOSE: Creates a normal requester.
     ARGS:   text - the text within the requester.
                    Linefeed via '||'
                    Example: "Hello, folks||Here I am!"
           gadget - the text of the gadgets. Every gadget text has to
                    be seperated via '|'.
                    Example: "Retry|Ignore|Cancel"

* COMMAND: @{fg fill}ReqFile@{fg text} [@{b}hail@{ub}:Str] [@{b}yourFile@{ub}:Str]
  PURPOSE: brings an ASL file requester on the player's screen.
     ARGS:     hail - Requester's title
           yourFile - file preset

* COMMAND: @{fg fill}ReqDir@{fg text} [@{b}hail@{ub}:Str] [@{b}yourDir@{ub}:Str]
  PURPOSE: brings an ASL directory requester on the player's screen.
     ARGS:     hail - Requester's title
           yourFile - directory preset


* COMMAND: @{fg fill}ReqString@{fg text} [@{b}hail@{ub}:Str] [@{b}yourText@{ub}:Str]
  PURPOSE: brings a text requester on the player's screen
     ARGS:     hail - title text
           yourText - text preset
___________________________________________________________________

* COMMAND: @{fg fill}SetWaitPointer@{fg text}
  PURPOSE: Sets the waiting pointer...
     ARGS: -

* COMMAND: @{fg fill}ResetPointer@{fg text}
  PURPOSE: ...and back to the normal pointer.
     ARGS: -
___________________________________________________________________

* COMMAND: @{fg fill}RunShell@{fg text}
  PURPOSE: A shell will be launched on the player's screen.
           You can change the launching command via "SetShellCom"
     ARGS: -

* COMMAND: @{fg fill}RunEditor@{fg text}
  PURPOSE: An editor will be launched on the player's screen.
           Change the concerning command via "SetEditorCom".
           Using the standard setting, you have to copy the
           original Commodore "Ed" into your C: directory!
     ARGS: -

* COMMAND: @{fg fill}SetShellCom@{fg text} [@{b}comStr@{ub}:Str]
  PURPOSE: To set the command string to be executed when
           using the "RunShell" command. Preset is:
           @{i}NewShell "CON:20/10/500/130/MMPlayer Shell/CLOSE/SCREENMMPlayer"@{ui}
     ARGS: -

* COMMAND: @{fg fill}SetEditorCom@{fg text} [@{b}comStr@{ub}:Str]
  PURPOSE: To set the command string to be executed when
           using the "RunEditor" command. Preset is:
           @{i}C:Ed FROM dummy WINDOW
             CON:20/10/530/150/Editor/CLOSE/SCREENMMPlayer@{ui}
           This will work with the original Commodore "Ed" from your
           workbench disk.
     ARGS: -
___________________________________________________________________

* COMMAND: @{fg fill}LoadBrush@{fg text} [@{b}filename@{ub}:Str]
  PURPOSE: load a IFF ILBM brush file from disk
     ARGS: Str - filename

* COMMAND: @{fg fill}CutBrush@{fg text} [@{b}x@{ub}:Int] [@{b}y@{ub}:Int] [@{b}w@{ub}:Int] [@{b}h@{ub}:Int]
  PURPOSE: cut a brush from the player's screen.
     ARGS: x - left edge of cutting area
           y - top egde of cutting area
           w - width of cutting area
           h - height of cutting area

* COMMAND: @{fg fill}CopyBrush@{fg text} [@{b}x@{ub}:Int] [@{b}y@{ub}:Int] [@{b}w@{ub}:Int] [@{b}h@{ub}:Int]
  PURPOSE: copy a brush from the player's screen.
     ARGS: x - left edge of copying area
           y - top egde of copying area
           w - width of copying area
           h - height of copying area

* COMMAND: @{fg fill}PasteBrush@{fg text} [@{b}x@{ub}:Int] [@{b}y@{ub}:Int]
  PURPOSE: paste the brush loaded by LoadBrush or copied/cutted from
           the screen into the player's screen on position x, y
     ARGS: x - x position
           y - y position

* COMMAND: @{fg fill}BrushPalette@{fg text} [@{b}on@{ub}:Bool]
  PURPOSE: Switch to the color palette of the loaded brush
     ARGS: on=1 - use brush palette
           on=0 - reset to original palette

* COMMAND: @{fg fill}FreeBrush@{fg text}
  PURPOSE: Deallocates the current loaded/copied/cutted brush
           and frees its memory
     ARGS: -
     NOTE: You @{i}have@{ui} to free the brush's memory on your own!
___________________________________________________________________

* COMMAND: @{fg fill}SetColor@{fg text} [nr:Int] [r:Int] [g:int] [b:Int]
  PURPOSE: change any color of the current palette
     ARGS: nr - of color to change
            r -
            g -
            b - the red, green and blue parts of the color

* COMMAND: @{fg fill}DrawColor@{fg text} [nr:Int]
  PURPOSE: sets the current drawing color.
     ARGS: nr - of color

* COMMAND: @{fg fill}DrawPixel@{fg text} [x:Int] [y:Int]
  PURPOSE: Draws a pixel on position x, y in the current drawing color
     ARGS: x - horicontal position
           y - vertival position

* COMMAND: @{fg fill}DrawLine@{fg text} [x1:Int] [y1:Int] [x2:Int] [y2:Int]
  PURPOSE: Draws a line from x1, y2 to x2,y2
     ARGS: look above!

* COMMAND: @{fg fill}DrawRectangle@{fg text} [x1:Int] [y1:Int] [x2:Int] [y2:Int]
  PURPOSE: Draws a rectangle from x1, y2 to x2,y2
     ARGS: look above!

* COMMAND: @{fg fill}DrawRectFill@{fg text} [x1:Int] [y1:Int] [x2:Int] [y2:Int]
  PURPOSE: Draws a filled rectangle from x1, y2 to x2,y2
     ARGS: look above!

* COMMAND: @{fg fill}DrawCircle@{fg text} [x1:Int] [y1:Int] [x2:Int] [r:Int]
  PURPOSE: Draws a circle with the middle in x1, x2 and
           the radius r
     ARGS: look above!

* COMMAND: @{fg fill}DrawText@{fg text} [x1:Int] [y1:Int] [text:Str]
  PURPOSE: Prints the text on position x1, y2
     ARGS:   x1 - x position
             y1 - y position
           text - the text to print

* COMMAND: @{fg fill}FloodFill@{fg text} [x1:Int] [y1:Int]
  PURPOSE: fills the area from x1, y2
     ARGS: x1 - x position
           y1 - y position
___________________________________________________________________

* COMMAND: @{fg fill}Query@{fg text} [@{b}what@{ub}:Str]
  PURPOSE: Gives some information about the current menu.
           The result will be stored in the ARexx variable RESULT.
     ARGS:      PLLEFT - left edge of player's screen
                 PLTOP - top edge of player's screen
               PLWIDTH - width of player's screen
              PLHEIGHT - height of player's screen
              PLHEIGHT - number of planes used by the player's screen
              PLCOLORS - number of colors used by the player's screen
           MMREXXDEBUG - debug mode on?
              ISGERMAN - german language currently used?

* COMMAND: @{fg fill}FileExists@{fg text} [@{b}filename@{ub}:Str]
  PURPOSE: Does the given filename exist?
           If RESULT=0 then NO, else if RESULT=1 then YES, it is
           existing.
     ARGS: filename - Filename of the file to test.

* COMMAND: @{fg fill}WaitForLMB@{fg text}
  PURPOSE: stops menu's execution until user press either the left
           mouse button or the space key.
     ARGS: -
     NOTE: The displaying of the Displays (time, memory,...)
           will also stop!
___________________________________________________________________

* COMMAND: @{fg fill}MMRexxDebug@{fg text} [@{b}on@{ub}:Bool]
  PURPOSE: Switching debug-mode. In this mode,
           every time, the player receives a rexx command,
           a requester is giving out this command and it's arguments.
     ARGS: on=0 no debugging
             =1 debug mode on.
@endnode

@node "PlayerScr" "MMPlayer's screen"
MMPlayer opens a @{b}public screen@{ub} for displaying the iff picture. Thus you can
use any screen from third party programs. For example, you can start the
workbench program 'Clock' on the MMPlayer's screen via the SCREEN option
when starting from CLI.

The public screen's name is @{b}MMPlayer@{ub} (MMPlayer_1 if loaded twice)


Example: How to open the shell on the MMPlayer screen

          1> NewShell CON:0/0/400/100/MyShell/SCREENMMPlayer


Please confer you manual to get more information about public screens.
@endnode

@node "PlayerIco" "Iconification of MMPlayer"
Since Version 3.21 you can close the screen of MMPlayer - the menu - while
running the menu (@{b}iconification mode@{ub}).

This is working via the ARexx commands Iconify or Sleep:

 · @{"Iconify" link "PlayerRexx" 28}      The screen disappears, an AppIcon is appearing on the
                workbench. Just click on the AppIcon and the screen
                will be re-opened again.

                The AppIcon's filename is: "@{i}PROGDIR:M&M.appicon.info@{ui}"

                You can also put an icon on the AppIcon - in this
                case, the icon's filename will be stored to
                the environment variable "@{i}MMAPPFILENAME@{ui}" and can
                be used in your menu (for example startup commands)

 · @{"Sleep" link "PlayerRexx" 28}        The screen disappears. Nothing more - especially
                @{b}no AppIcon@{ub} is appearing.
                You have to "wake" MMPlayer via the ARexx command Wake.


To re-open the menu again (the IFF screen file will be loaded again) you can
use

 · @{"Uniconify" link "PlayerRexx" 28} or

 · @{"Wake" link "CommRxx" 28}


Please notice the ARexx script called

   @{i}ARexx/Wake.rexx@{ui}

for waking purposes (type in your shell: @{i}RX wake@{ui})
@endnode

@node "MMReq" "MMReq - Menus & More Requester Tool"
MMReq is a short tool program to @{b}display a requester on the player screen@{ub}.
It can easily implemented within AmigaDos scripts.

Unfortunately, it has not been completed yet! :-(

At time, you can only use @{b}Okay/Cancel@{ub} or @{b}Yes/No@{ub} requesters.

You can call it in the following way:

  MMReq [reqText] [reqType]

  reqType can be "OKCANC" or "YESNO"

If the player's screen is open, a requester will be displayed upon it. If
the user selects the negative answer ("cancel" or "no"), an AmigaDos return
code 10 (=FAIL) will be returned. If the player is not active, an error
message appears.


Example: How to call MMReq within an AmigaDos script

        Failat 20
        MMReq YESNO "Copy textfiles to ram disk?"
        IF NOT ERROR
          Copy #?.txt to RAM:
        ENDIF
        MMReq YESNO "Keep old files?"
        IF ERROR
          Delete #?.txt
        ENDIF


Another example is in the "@{i}Install.bat@{ui}" file, which is called by the M&M
project "@{i}Installation.M&M@{ui}"

Please notice that you can use the character "|" as a linefeed!
@endnode

@node "MMAnalyse" "MMAnalyse - The Menus & More Analyse Tool"
Basically, the only task of MMAnalyse is @{b}to print out the filenames of all
IFF screens@{ub} used by a M&M menu project.

MMEditor stores those filenames to the project file. When running the menu,
it could happen that the Player cannot find a screen file. With MMAnalyse
you are able to find out which screens the player tries to load.

Another possible application: If you want to copy a complete menu project
@{i}with@{ui} the screen files, you can create a list:

   1> Copy `MMAnalyse Drawer/MyProject.M&M` to SOURCE:


Get more information about every screen (like resolution or startup
commands) by giving the @{b}FULL@{ub} option.


@{u}Start from workbench@{uu}

  · click on the project's icon, press shift and click on the
    MMAnalyse icon or

  · click on the MMAnalyse icon and select a file within the
    file requester

  Note: The @{b}FULL@{ub} option is switched on as standard when starting
        from Workbench. It can be discarded by the ToolType

          FULL=OFF


@{u}Start from CLI@{uu}

  · type

    1> MMAnalyse [project] [FULL/S]
@endnode

@node "Examples" "Example menu projects"
With V3.21, all examples are @{b}re-designed@{ub}. Most of them are based upon a
beautiful (?) background picture. Those picture were all taken from the
AmiNet Set CDs and have been re-formatted using PPaint®.

They all have the @{b}same set of gadgets@{ub} below the titlebar (implemented by
using the ARexx commands "Iconify", "RunShell" and "RunEditor"). If you want
to implement these buttons in your own menus: the brush files are stored in
the @{i}Examples@{ui} directory.

All example projects try to load their screens using the filename

    @{i}PROGDIR:Examples/Picturename.pic@{ui}


Please have a @{b}closer look at the example projects@{ub} as they might contain some
interesting or helpful clues for you...


@{fg fill}FirstExample.M&M@{fg text}        For a first look and to understand the
                        implementation of buttons - try to set the
                        concerning commands using MMEditor!

@{fg fill}TestLab.M&M@{fg text}             For testing all possibilites of M&M. The current
                        directory will be printed after start, so don't
                        worry, the menu needs some time to start...

@{fg fill}BigFuncTest.M&M@{fg text}         like the one above, but opens a huge screen for
                        demonstrating the auto-scroll function.
                        You will need the ECS chipset.

@{fg fill}ARexxTest.M&M@{fg text}           a menu which demonstrates some features of
                        the MMPlayer's ARexx-Port.

@{fg fill}Dubios.M&M@{fg text}              An example menu designed for the public-domain
                        mail order "Dubios & Co"...

ErstesBeispiel.M&M      the german first example menu
@endnode

@node "HighScore" "Saving the High Score"
@{fg highlight}SAVING THE HIGH SCORE ?!?!@{fg text}


Hey, this NOT A GAME!

All you can do with this piece of software is the production of
graphic-orientated menus.


   @{"   Gulp?!   " link "AboutMM" 0}
@endnode

@node "Versions" "Versions..."
@{fg highlight}3.00@{fg text}
  - final release

@{fg highlight}3.01@{fg text}
  - now running with the AGA chipset (A1200/4000)

@{fg highlight}3.02@{fg text}
  - internal change

@{fg highlight}3.10@{fg text}
  - new shareware concept
  - improved user interface (GUI)
  - new ToolTypes
  - better error-handling while executing AmigaDos commands,
    asynchron running
  - copy commands
  - full AGA support
  - new project file format (will be converted automatically)

@{fg highlight}3.11@{fg text}
  - bug-fixing

@{fg highlight}3.12@{fg text}
  - locale-support, first international version
  - bug-fixing

@{fg highlight}3.13@{fg text}
  - more ARexx commands
  - project installation within MMEditor
  - new installation procedure using ARexx
  - some new project examples
  - individual setting of the bit-planes used by MMEditor
  - new Dos Command-Option: Set WaitPointer
  - || as linefeed in requester texts
  - improved error messages
  - request before MMEditor executes a startup-command
  - bug-fixing


@{fg highlight}3.14@{fg text}
  - no more problems with asyncron running dos commands
  - error in installation.rexx fixed

@{fg highlight}3.20@{fg text}

  - New command: Show Brush (also via ARexx commands)
  - Much improved IFF ILBM reading routine
    with correct 32 bit (AGA) colortable reading
  - New options when running dos commands:
    Priority and Current directory
  - Possibilty to clear all environment variables used by
    MMPlayer when quitting the menu
  - Testrun gadget in the Screens-Window
  - Better requester positioning
  - the usual bug fixing...

@{fg highlight}3.21@{fg text}
  - Iconify (with or without AppIcon, via ARexx)
  - Small editor for requester texts
  - now | (instead of ||) as linefeeder in requester texts
  - after screen loading error, possibilty to select
    an alternative menu screen
  - pulldown menus: real intuition barlabels supported
  - new Arexx commands for an easy way of launching
    a shell or an editor
  - MMEditor can be started with system font or topaz.8
    (ToolType TOPAZEIGHT)
  - completely new designed examples
  - MagicWB Icons
  - bug fix

@{fg highlight}3.22 - the actual version@{fg text}
  - bug fixed version


